  abstract = {We study Bayesian hypernetworks: a framework for approximate Bayesian inference in neural networks. A Bayesian hypernetwork h is a neural network which learns to transform a simple noise distribution, p( ) = N (0, I), to a distribution q(\texttheta ) := q(h( )) over the parameters \texttheta{} of another neural network (the ``primary network''). We train q with variational inference, using an invertible h to enable efficient estimation of the variational lower bound on the posterior p(\texttheta\textbar D) via sampling. In contrast to most methods for Bayesian deep learning, Bayesian hypernets can represent a complex multimodal approximate posterior with correlations between parameters, while enabling cheap iid sampling of q(\texttheta ). In practice, Bayesian hypernets can provide a better defense against adversarial examples than dropout, and also exhibit competitive performance on a suite of tasks which evaluate model uncertainty, including regularization, active learning, and anomaly detection.},
